Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add @salt{0.25%tsp} and stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into 1cm pieces). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed and quartered lengthways, chopped widthways into small pieces), then quarter lengthways (no need to peel). Chop widthways into small pieces. Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{150%g}(trimmed and chopped into thirds) and chop into thirds. Trim the @courgette{1}(trimmed, quartered lengthways and cut into 1cm chunks) .

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium heat and add the onion and carrot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{6-7%minutes}. Stir in the @tandoori masala spice{1%tsp} and a pinch of @chilli flakes{1%pinch} (don't add too much, they're hot!) and cook for ~{30%seconds}. Now add the @ginger puree{1/2%tsp}, garlic and @tomato puree{30%g}, stir and cook for another ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in the @water{250%ml} for the curry, half the @reduced fat creme fraiche{112.5%g}, @coconut powder{50%g} and @vegetable stock powder{1%tsp}. Bring to the boil, stirring to dissolve the coconut powder, then reduce the heat to medium, stir in the green beans and courgette and simmer until the liquid has reduced by half and thickened and the veggies are cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). When the curry is cooked, season to taste with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if needed (now is the time to add some more chilli flakes if you want more kick!).

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}. Serve the rice in #bowls{} topped with plenty of veggie tikka, a drizzle of remaining creme fraiche and a sprinkling of coriander. Enjoy!

> When it comes to creating deliciously simple vegetarian recipes, Chef Mimi is the expert. Packed with fresh, colourful veg, her take on this classic curry recipe won't disappoint. Traditionally, onion and ginger provide the deep base flavour of most curries, but deciding how to cook them will determine the flavour of your final dish. Soften them without colouring for a lighter curry (like this one) or cook them longer and caramelise for something richer and darker.